  <compounddef id="BITROR" kind="page">
    <compoundname>BITROR</compoundname>
    <title>BITROR Keyword</title>
    <briefdescription>
    </briefdescription>
    <detaileddescription>
<para><programlisting filename=".basic"><codeline><highlight class="normal">X<sp/>=<sp/>BITROR(a,<sp/>n,<sp/>width)</highlight></codeline>
</programlisting></para>
<para>Rotates integer <computeroutput>a</computeroutput> <bold>right</bold> by <computeroutput>n</computeroutput> bits within a given <computeroutput>width</computeroutput>.</para>
<para><hruler/>
</para>
<sect3 id="BITROR_1autotoc_md183">
<title>How to read it</title>
<para><itemizedlist>
<listitem><para>Only the lowest <computeroutput>width</computeroutput> bits participate in the rotation.</para>
</listitem><listitem><para>Width is typically 1–64.</para>
</listitem><listitem><para>Result is masked back to the chosen width.</para>
</listitem></itemizedlist>
</para>
<para><hruler/>
</para>
</sect3>
<sect3 id="BITROR_1autotoc_md185">
<title>Examples</title>
<para><programlisting filename=".basic"><codeline><highlight class="normal">PRINT<sp/>BITROR(&amp;9,<sp/>1,<sp/>4)</highlight></codeline>
</programlisting></para>
<para>This rotates <computeroutput>1001₂</computeroutput> right by one within 4 bits, giving <computeroutput>1100₂ = 12</computeroutput>.</para>
<para><hruler/>
</para>
</sect3>
<sect3 id="BITROR_1autotoc_md187">
<title>Notes</title>
<para><itemizedlist>
<listitem><para>Operates on 64-bit integers.</para>
</listitem><listitem><para>Rotation width must be chosen carefully; too small discards low bits.</para>
</listitem></itemizedlist>
</para>
